Macros

macro `\>`(value, call): untyped
same as |> except allows multiple arguments for value in the form of (a, b)

Example:

import ../applicates

const incr = toApplicate(system.succ)
const multiply = toApplicate(`*`)
const divide = toApplicate(`/`)

let foo = (3, 2) \>
  multiply \>
  incr \>
  14.divide
doAssert foo == 2
  Source   Edit 
macro `\`(call: untyped): untyped

converts a call expression to an applicate call expression

supports dot calls, if the given expression is not a dot expression or call or command then it will simply apply it with no arguments

Example:

import ../applicates
const foo = x ==> x + 1
doAssert \foo(1) == 2
doAssert \1.foo == 2
const bar = (a, b) ==> a + b
doAssert \bar(1, 2) == 3
doAssert \1.bar(2) == 3
const baz = ==> 10
doAssert \baz() == 10
doAssert \baz == 10
  Source   Edit 
macro `|>`(value, call): untyped

inserts value as first argument of call, and converts it to applicate call expression

if call is a dot call, it is not modified, so value becomes the second argument in the call

Example:

import ../applicates

const incr = toApplicate(system.succ)
const multiply = toApplicate(`*`)
const divide = toApplicate(`/`)

let foo = 3 |>
  multiply(2) |>
  incr |>
  14.divide
doAssert foo == 2
  Source   Edit 
macro chain(initial, calls): untyped
statement list chained version of |>

Example:

import ../applicates

const incr = toApplicate(system.succ)
const multiply = toApplicate(`*`)
const divide = toApplicate(`/`)

let foo = chain 3:
  multiply 2
  incr
  14.divide
doAssert foo == 2
